{{hatnote|See also [[Dyadic space (disambiguation)]]}}
The '''dyadic space''' is the name for the volume of [[cytoplasm]] between pairs (dyads) of areas where the [[cell membrane]] and an [[organelle]] such as the [[endoplasmic reticulum]] (or [[sarcoplasmic reticulum]]) come into close contact (within 10-12 nanometers<ref> {{cite journal |last=Koh |last2=Srinivasan |last3=Ching |last4=Levchenko |year=2006 |title=A 3D Monte Carlo Analysis of the Role of Dyadic Space Geometry in Spark Generation |journal=Biophysical Journal |publisher=Elsevier |volume=90 |issue=6 |pages=1999–2014 |doi=10.1529/biophysj.105.065466 |pmid=16387773 |pmc=1386779}}<!--|access-date=28 July 2015--> </ref>) of each other, creating what are known as ''dyadic clefts''. <ref>{{cite journal |last=Page |first= |last2=Buecker |first2= |year=1981 |title=Development of Dyadic Junctional Complexes between Sarcoplasmic Reticulum and Plasmalemma in Rabbit Left Ventricular Myocardial Cells |journal=Circulation Research |publisher= |volume=48 |issue=4 |pages=519–522 |doi=10.1161/01.RES.48.4.519 }}<!--|access-date=28 July 2015--> </ref>
The space is important for ionic signalling. For example, the phenomenon of ''calcium-induced calcium release'',<ref> {{cite journal |last=Cannell |last2=Kong |last3=Imtiaz |last4=Laver |year=2013 |title=Control of sarcoplasmic reticulum Ca2+ release by stochastic RyR gating within a 3D model of the cardiac dyad and importance of induction decay for CICR termination. |journal=Biophysical Journal |publisher=Elsevier |volume=104 |issue=10 |pages=2149–59 |doi=10.1016/j.bpj.2013.03.058 |pmid=23708355 |pmc=3660628}}<!--|access-date=28 July 2015--> </ref> when extracellular calcium enters the cell through [[ion channels]] in [[T-Tubule]]s, leading to a rapidly increased calcium concentration in the dyadic space, triggering [[ryanodine receptor]]s on the [[sarcoplasmic reticulum]] to release more calcium and trigger [[cardiac myocyte]] contraction - the heart beat.
